posts.author: expedia.com
posts.text: Atlantis was a very beautiful experience for me and my husband. Our view from our Royal Towers room was breathtaking, the grounds were well kept & the beach was clean and crystal clear waters. Staff were extremely friendly & welcoming. If you stay at the Royal Towers you’re literally right in the middle of everything! Major plus! They give you free water vouchers to use during your stay which helped!! The only thing that didn’t please me was the food, being we came at off season, the lunch options were limited to overly priced fried foods or sandwiches & food in general here is very expensive. You can look at spending anywhere from $100-250 a day alone per couple. Some restaurants that I would recommended is Bahamian Club or Mosaic for dinner & Poseidon’s for breakfast buffet, both were very tasty. Do not eat at Nobu, you pay for ambiance only. Service wasn’t that great & they messed up our steak twice! They did however remove it off the bill & dessert was good. Aura nightclub was fun, and if you like to gamble the casino was very nice too! Relax by the pool and enjoy the water slides & lazy river! Overall we loved our experience here at Atlantis and would recommend everyone to stay here! Thanks for lasting memories!

I did online dating for a while. I was commuting to college, working full-time, etc so it was hard to meet someone.
I learned that 99% of the women who are online are nuts in one way or another. Many of the profiles are scams (Tinder is full of that) or the women think extremely highly of themselves or have social issues. Self-confidence is important, but so is self-awareness. Many of them are also not single, and are either looking to cheat, or are in abusive relationships they don't know how to get out of.

I also met a few really nice women online, but those seemed far and few between, and many of them were like me and were on there because they had busy schedules, which didn't make things any easier.
I found a lot them had social issues, and it was very apparent on the first date. I'm very outgoing, I like to have fun, play sports, etc, and many of these women seemed to have a hard time communicating or being exposed to social situations. It takes guts, but I found the best thing to do is go to a social event and approach someone. Talk to them, and within the first few minutes you can get a good idea of who you are dealing with and if the person is worth it or not. Pictures online can also be deceiving (good or bad) compared to in person.

1) You have to look at your policy to see what it states. Contrary to popular belief, there are clauses that state the insurance company can use aftermarket or equivalent parts. I went through this recently with State Farm and Liberty Mutual. We were not at fault and the car was never in a wreck before this incident. You have to work with a good body shop. They know how to "work" the system. The body shop I took our car to followed the rules and came up with justifications on why OEM was necessary. And because they have a relationship with the dealer we bought our car from, they were able to match aftermarket pricing with OEM parts. The insurance company was happy, they're happy because they still made a profit, and we're happy because we have OEM new parts.
2) I've never heard of this issue with the rental car. My understanding is rental car coverage is only for situations where you the insured have to get a rental car because your car is in the shop for body work. In your situation, rental car coverage should be charged against the at fault person's liability coverage. The only time rental car coverage becomes an issue is if the fault isn't determined early and you have to use your own coverage to get your car fixed while the insurance companies battle it out.

posts.title: Victory eye shot up A-League ladder
posts.text:
Victory eye shot up A-League ladder Melbourne Victory coach Kevin Muscat believes his side answered A-League questions by responding to a 2-0 deficit against Wellington Phoenix last week.
The top four has seemed a world away for underperforming A-League giants Melbourne Victory this season, but it's the prize on offer this Friday night against Adelaide United.
And on their recent form against their oldest rivals, you'd be tempted to lock it in.
Victory have lost just once in 13 fixtures anywhere against the Reds, and only once at Etihad Stadium in the last decade.
After a season of struggle, Kevin Muscat's side are in a bright mood after their comeback 3-2 win over Wellington last week.
Embed from Getty Images
"It was a big challenge for the group," Muscat said of their two-goal escape against the Phoenix.
"We questioned them and asked them to make a decision: Are you going to maintain belief - or, the easiest thing to do at that point in time which was to accept their fate?
"As a group they stood up.
"The care factor was obvious to everyone. Coupled together with the mental side, their attitude and their ability was devastating."
Mark Milligan's availability is another bonus as Victory searches for a first home win this campaign.
But Muscat warned their recent record of domination didn't "guarantee a result".
"In Wellington we created an abundance of chances and opportunities, which is what we are about and how we want to be seen by other teams," he said.
"This week has been a refocus to make sure we reproduce that type of performance. If we do we give ourselves a great chance."
After three games on the road, Victory have just one trip outside Victoria - a visit to John Aloisi's struggling Brisbane - in the next month.
In contrast, United have away days against Victory, Newcastle, Perth and Western Sydney in the same run.
The Reds will be without Karim Matmour, who left the club on compassionate grounds this week, and injured Danish winger Johan Absalonsen.
But Vince Lia is poised to return from a knee injury, for the first time since a double in Adelaide's 2-2 draw with Victory in October.
Ex-City fullbacks Michael Marrone and Ben Garuccio are also available after serving suspensions.
STATS THAT MATTER
* Victory have a super record against Adelaide, with just one loss in a decade at Etihad Stadium against the Reds.
* But Kevin Muscat's side is drawing blanks at home. They haven't scored more than one in a home fixture since March.
* If Adelaide does triumph, it will be the first time the Reds have managed back-to-back away wins in 20 months.
